                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1645">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 704.6712/3.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Morgenthau</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 199.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Constantinople</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-01-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 30, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In acknowledgment of the Department’s telegram
                    No. 257 of the 10th [11th] instant, stating that American officers in Mexico <pb
                        facs="1190" n="1074" xml:id="pg_1074"/> have been authorized to use their
                    good offices in that country for Turkish subjects, I have the honor to state
                    that this information has been communicated to the Sublime Porte. This was done
                    verbally, owing to the fact that the request which formed the subject of the
                    Embassy’s telegram of September 21 was a verbal one.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">A. Morgenthau.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
